Introduction¶

Project interest¶

Nowadays, mobile applications are part of our daily lives. They now account for more than half (52%) of the time spent on digital media on the one hand, and would account for 89% of the time spent by users of on their smartphone.Thereby, it is not surprising that since 2016, the market for mobile applications has experienced unprecedented growth. It is now worth billions of dollars, through the marketing of mobile games in particular, and it explains the attractivity of this market for developers and investors.

Number of available apps in the Apple App Store from 2008 to 2020 (Source : Statista)

In reality, the market for applications is rather centralised, especially on platforms such as the App Store or the Play Store. These sites contain a lot of information about applications, and it would be useful to exploit them. For instance, it would be interesting to develop a decision-making tool, particularly for developers, to better understand market expectations and predict whether a certain type of application will potentially be more successful than another. Also, such a tool could be quite useful for investors, or for the previously cited app stores, which could improve their recommandation systems.

Bearing this in mind, one can wonder whether it is possible to predict the success of an app on the app store from the information available about this application.

We will focus on mobile games, since they represent a large share of the mobile application market.

Performance indicator¶

First of all, we need to define the notion of succes of an application. There are two obvious ways of defining this success:

  1. The average rating given to the application
  2. The number of downloads

For our study, we should really take into account both criterions. Indeed, if we only focus on ratings, an app with a rating of 5 stars and which was downloaded only 20 times would have a higher "success" than another one with 4 stars but 20 000 downloads. On the other hand, by only considering the downloads, an app with a rating of 3 and 1000 downloads would be more successful than the one with a rating of 4 and 500 downloads. It is true that for an investor, the success would be mostly linked to the number of downloads. For a developer, the satisfaction of the users may be his top priority. What we want to show here is that coming up with a "fully objective" criterion to measure the success of an application is not an easy task, and is mostly subjective.

In order to satisfy both worlds, we will define arbitrarily success as the total rating received by the application, averaged over its age. To make things clear, we have:

$$ Success_{total} = Average Rating \times NbRatings $$

Such a criterion would most likely penalize the newest applications compared to the oldest ones, so we need to take into account the "age" of the app:

$$ Success = \frac{Average Rating \times NbRatings}{Age} $$

with the age for instance in months.

One remark is that we actually do not use the number of downloads in our "succes score". This is due tot he fact that the number of downloads is not available in the database, that we will present in the next section. But still, we can assume that there is a high correlation between the number of downloads and the number of ratings, so the later feature partially compensates for the absence of the other.

Origin of the database¶

The data that will be used in this project are obtained by scraping on the Apple Store, particularly games applications which have a lot of user feedback.

The scraping we did was made possible thanks to APIs made available by Apple. We have in particular used App Store Sitemap to retrieve the "id" of applications.These are used in iTunes Search API to retrieve details about the applications that make up the main features of our database.

Description of the scraping:¶

  • Collecting application's URLs

The App Store is organized by category, here we took the Games category. In each category, the applications are listed by letter and there is the possibility to have several pages for each letter.

So at first it was important to know what was the number of pages per letter in order to be able to retrieve the "id" of the corresponding applications. Also we used this to limit the number of pages per letter from which scraped the features (we took 70% of the pages per letter). To achieve this, we created intermediate functions to, among other things, generate the URL of a page from the associated letter and its page number.

  • Scraping of application items:

First we observed the different items available for each application. Then we chose the features that could help us best answer to our problem of determining the success of an application. We used three of these features to calculate what would be a success and removed them from our covariates to avoid biasing the learning of success.

Definition of the problem¶

  • Aim: Predict the success (as defined above) of an application. This output is in $\mathbb{R}$

  • Scoring: As we have a continuous output, what comes in hand is the Mean square error defined as follows: $$MSE = {\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2} $$ We also compute the RMSE wich is define as $\sqrt{MSE} $ it can be compared with the typical value of the output. And then we consider a normalize RSME by dividing the RSME by the standard deviation of the output.

Here we use a Random Forest to predict the output $\hat{y}$ but any efficient strategy to predict a continuous output could be conceivable.

#Encoding of the categorical variable "contentAdvisoryRating"
def contentAdvisoryRating_recode(val):
    if val=='4_plus':
        output = 1
    elif val == '9_plus':
        output = 2
    elif val == '12_plus':
        output = 3
    else:
        output = 4
    return output

Creation of new features¶

To exploit properly some features already present in our database, we need to create new ones:

  • Age of the app (Current date - Release date)
  • Release month (Month of the release date)
  • Months since last update
  • Number of languages available
  • Languages available (boolean, for the top 10 languages)
  • Number of (sub) categories
  • Categories
  • Application size
  • Experience of the developper

The age of the application (in months) is important, especially since it will be used when computing the success score. It also allows us to use properly the release date.

Another useful information with teh release date is the month of release. Indeed, we can assume that it wil have an impact on the number of downloads.

The number of months since the last update give us an idea of whether the application is still maintained. One can expect that a successful application will be regularly maintained.

The number of languages available allows us to further use the feature "languageCodesISO2A": if the app supports many languages, it may attract more users.

The languages available are deduced from the previous feature "languageCodesISO2A", but this new feature is actually usable (it becomes a boolean of whether one of the top languages is present or not).

Number of sub categories may help: the higher, the more likely is the user to find it when searching a specific sub category.

Categories are deduced from the previous feature "genres", but this new feature is actually usable (it becomes a boolean of whether one of the top languages is present or not).

Application size give us a hint of whether there is a lot of content in the app.

Experience of the developer is based on the number of games developped by the developper.

Age of the app (already given in the json file)¶

In [30]:
def date_diff(d1, d2):
    """Returns the difference between two dates in months"""
    d1 = datetime.strptime(d1[:10], "%Y-%m-%d")
    d2 = datetime.strptime(d2, "%Y-%m-%d")
    return round(abs((d2 - d1)).days*(12/365),2)

def get_month(d1):
    """Return release month of application """
    return datetime.strptime(d1[:10], "%Y-%m-%d").strftime('%m-%b')

In [53]:
# Search unique languages
def search_languages(data):
    unique_lang = []
    for list_lang in data.languageCodesISO2A:
        for lang in list_lang:
            if unique_lang.count(lang)==0:
                unique_lang.append(lang)
    return unique_lang  


def dummy_langue(sub_liste,liste):
    '''Fonction qui cre autant de variables dummies qu'il y a de langues disponibles pour l'application
    
    Input:
        sub_liste: cellule qcq de la variable 'languageCodesISO2A'
        liste: liste des langues disponibles'''
    
    results=[]
    for elt in liste:
        y = (sub_liste.count(elt)!=0)*1 #lt est dans sous liste ?
        results.append(y)
        
    return results

def create_lang_df(data):
    unique_lang = search_languages(data)
    data_lang = data.languageCodesISO2A.apply(lambda x:dummy_langue(x, unique_lang))
    data_lang = data_lang.apply(pd.Series)
    data_lang = data_lang.rename(columns=dict(zip(range(132),unique_lang))) 
    data_lang.index = data.id_app

    return data_lang

def search_languages_top(data_lang, nb):
    cum_lang = data_lang.sum(axis = 0).sort_values(ascending=False)
    top_lang = list(cum_lang[0:10].index)
    return top_lang

def search_genres(data):
    unique_genre = []
    for list_genre in data.genres:
        for genre in list_genre:
            if unique_genre.count(genre)==0:
                unique_genre.append(genre)  
    return unique_genre  


def dummy_genre(sub_liste,liste):
    '''Fonction qui cre autant de variables dummies qu'il y a de genres
       pour l'application 
    
    Input:
        sub_liste: cellule qcq de la variable 'Genres'
        liste: dfinition en extansion de la variable Genres'''
    
    results=[]
    for elt in liste:
        y = (sub_liste.count(elt)!=0)*1 #lt est dans sous liste ?
        results.append(y)
        
    return results

def create_genre_df(data):
    unique_genre = search_genres(data)
    data_genre = data.genres.apply(lambda x:dummy_genre(x, unique_genre))
    data_genre = data_genre.apply(pd.Series)
    data_genre = data_genre.rename(columns=dict(zip(range(len(unique_genre)),unique_genre))) 
    data_genre.index = data.id_app  

    return data_genre

def search_genres_top(data_genre, nb):
    cum_genres = data_genre.sum(axis = 0).sort_values(ascending=False)
    top_genre = list(cum_genres[:nb].index)
    return top_genre

Corresponding function for the pipeline:¶

In [75]:
def process_database(data):

    date_end ="2019-12-10" # The date from which the age is computed

    data['age_app'] = data.releaseDate.apply(lambda x : date_diff(x, date_end))
    data['releaseMonth'] = data.releaseDate.apply(get_month)
    data['last_update'] = data.currentVersionReleaseDate.apply(lambda x : date_diff(x, date_end))
    data['nb_language'] = data.languageCodesISO2A.apply(len)

    data_lang = create_lang_df(data)
    top_lang = search_languages_top(data_lang, nb=10) # num top languages = 10
    data = data.merge(data_lang[top_lang], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_lang]

    data['genres'].apply(lambda s: s.remove('Games'))
    data['nb_genres'] = data.genres.apply(len)

    data_genre = create_genre_df(data)
    top_genre = search_genres_top(data_genre, nb=20) # num top genres = 20
    data = data.merge(data_genre[top_genre], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_genre]

    data.fileSizeBytes = pd.to_numeric(data.fileSizeBytes, errors='coerce')
    data['fileSizeMB']=data.fileSizeBytes.apply(lambda x : round(x/10**6,2))

    data_exp_dev = data[['sellerName','id_app']].groupby(by='sellerName', as_index=False).count()
    data_exp_dev.rename(columns={'id_app':'Exp_dev'}, inplace = True)
    data = data.merge(data_exp_dev, how='left', on='sellerName') # Will need to return data['Exp_dev']

    return np.c_[data['age_app'].values,
                 data['releaseMonth'].values,
                 data['last_update'].values,
                 data['nb_language'].values,
                 data[top_lang].values,
                 data['nb_genres'].values,
                 data[top_genre].values,
                 data['fileSizeMB'].values,
                 data['Exp_dev'].values]

Dependence between transformed features and transformed target

The log transformation of the features and the target makes it possible to reduce the skewness of the variables by giving less importance to the typical values of the variables which are very far by the right. This transformation then makes it possible to better appreciate the dependency between the covariates and the target. It can be pointed out that :

  • The most expensive applications are not necessarily the most successful on the appstore. Indeed, success seems to decrease when the price of the application is high.
  • A positive dependency between application success and size is observed, although for the heaviest applications, the relationship is less stable than for the smallest applications.

def process_database(data):

    data['contentAdvisoryRating'] = data['contentAdvisoryRating'].apply(lambda x : x.replace('+', '_plus'))
    data['contentAdvisoryRating'] = data['contentAdvisoryRating'].apply(contentAdvisoryRating_recode)

    data.price = pd.to_numeric(data.price, errors='coerce')

    date_end ="2019-12-10" # The date from which the age is computed

    data['age_app'] = data.releaseDate.apply(lambda x : date_diff(x, date_end))
    data['releaseMonth'] = data.releaseDate.apply(get_month)
    data['last_update'] = data.currentVersionReleaseDate.apply(lambda x : date_diff(x, date_end))
    data['nb_language'] = data.languageCodesISO2A.apply(len)

    data_lang = create_lang_df(data)
    top_lang = search_languages_top(data_lang, nb=10) # num top languages = 10
    data = data.merge(data_lang[top_lang], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_lang]

    #data['genres'].apply(lambda s: s.remove('Games'))
    data['nb_genres'] = data.genres.apply(len)

    data_genre = create_genre_df(data)
    top_genre = search_genres_top(data_genre, nb=20) # num top genres = 20
    data = data.merge(data_genre[top_genre], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_genre]

    sizes = pd.to_numeric(data.fileSizeBytes, errors='coerce')
    sizes = sizes.fillna(0)
    data['fileSizeMB']=sizes.apply(lambda x : np.log(round(x/10**6,2)+1))

    data_exp_dev = data[['sellerName','id_app']].groupby(by='sellerName', as_index=False).count()
    data_exp_dev.rename(columns={'id_app':'Exp_dev'}, inplace = True)
    data = data.merge(data_exp_dev, how='left', on='sellerName') # Will need to return data['Exp_dev']

    return np.c_[np.log( 1 + data['age_app'].values),
                 pd.get_dummies(data[['releaseMonth']]).values,
                 np.log(1 + data['last_update'].values),
                 np.log(1 + data['nb_language'].values),
                 data[top_lang].values,
                 data['nb_genres'].values,
                 data[top_genre].values,
                 np.log( 1 + data['fileSizeMB'].values),
                 np.log( 1 + data['Exp_dev'].values)]

        transformers=[

            ('drop cols', 'drop', drop),
        ], remainder='passthrough', n_jobs=-1)

Conclusion¶

The objective of this challenge is to predict the success of an application in a way that we have chosen here by observing the available features. It is therefore not an absolute metric to measure the success of an application, however we think it's a wise choice.

As far as the database is concerned, especially its improvement, there is some available features on the App Store that we did not take into account and that could have provided more information to determine the success of an application.

For instance, the images available on the application's description page (its logo and those presenting its content), which would imply a learning of features with a convolutional network on it. We also have the number of comments and their content which should be full of a lot of information that is correlated to the application's rating and therefore to its success. Indeed, a sentiment analysis carried out on these comments would allow a prediction of the score, for example. The difficulty here is that many applications do not have comments. However, this missing data could provide information on success in the sense that we could consider the absence of comments to be linked to a low download rate for example. Another textual data that we could consider is the description of each application, some keywords could promote the success of an application in the sense that we have defined it.

    data['releaseMonth'] = data.releaseDate.apply(get_month)
    data['last_update'] = data.currentVersionReleaseDate.apply(lambda x : date_diff(x, date_end))
    data['nb_language'] = data.languageCodesISO2A.apply(len)

    data_lang = create_lang_df(data)
    top_lang = search_languages_top(data_lang, nb=10) # num top languages = 10
    data = data.merge(data_lang[top_lang], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_lang]

    data['nb_genres'] = data.genres.apply(len)

    data_genre = create_genre_df(data)
    top_genre = search_genres_top(data_genre, nb=20) # num top genres = 20
    data = data.merge(data_genre[top_genre], how='inner', left_on='id_app', right_index=True) # Will need to return data[top_genre]

    sizes = pd.to_numeric(data.fileSizeBytes, errors='coerce')
    sizes = sizes.fillna(0)
    data['fileSizeMB']=sizes.apply(lambda x : np.log(round(x/10**6,2)+1))

    data_exp_dev = data[['sellerName','id_app']].groupby(by='sellerName', as_index=False).count()
    data_exp_dev.rename(columns={'id_app':'Exp_dev'}, inplace = True)
    data = data.merge(data_exp_dev, how='left', on='sellerName') # Will need to return data['Exp_dev']

    return np.c_[np.log( 1 + data['age_app'].values),
                 pd.get_dummies(data[['releaseMonth']]).values,
                 np.log(1 + data['last_update'].values),
                 np.log(1 + data['nb_language'].values),
                 data[top_lang].values,
                 data['nb_genres'].values,
                 data[top_genre].values,
                 np.log( 1 + data['fileSizeMB'].values),
                 np.log( 1 + data['Exp_dev'].values)]




def get_estimator():

    all_col = ['id_app', 'releaseDate', 'artworkUrl512', 'languageCodesISO2A',
       'fileSizeBytes', 'minimumOsVersion', 'trackName',
       'contentAdvisoryRating', 'genres', 'sellerName', 'formattedPrice',
       'price', 'currency', 'version', 'description',
       'currentVersionReleaseDate', 'age_app']

    drop = ['releaseDate', 'artworkUrl512', 'languageCodesISO2A', 'fileSizeBytes', 
        'trackName', 'genres', 'sellerName', 'formattedPrice', 'currency', 
        'description', 'currentVersionReleaseDate']

    database_transformer = FunctionTransformer(
        process_database, validate=False
    )

    preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
        transformers=[
            ('new_vars_and_process', database_transformer, all_col),
            ('drop cols', 'drop', drop),
        ], remainder='passthrough', n_jobs=-1)
    
    regressor = RandomForestRegressor(
            n_estimators=50, max_depth=20, max_features=.8, n_jobs=-1
        )

    pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessing', preprocessor),
        ('classifier', regressor)
    ])

    return pipeline

How to test and submit your solution .

  • Make sure you have installed ramp-workflow locally (see above)
  • Make sure that the python file estimator.py is in submissions/, and the train and test data are in data
  • If you haven't yet, download the data by executing python download_data.py
  • Finally, make sure the local processing goes through by running the

ramp-test --submission

If you want to quickly test the that there are no obvious code errors, use the --quick-test flag to only use a small subset of the data (training and testing sets with 5 elements each).

ramp-test --submission --quick-test

You can refer to the online documentation.
